title: The Writer's Garden: How Gardens Inspired our Best-loved Authors
author: Bennett, Jackie
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: What is it about readers and gardeners? Books and plants seem to combine so naturally for so many people. Maybe it’s because they are somewhat solitarWhat is it about readers and gardeners? Books and plants seem to combine so naturally for so many people. Maybe it’s because they are somewhat solitary activities which encourage introversion and self-reflection? Anyway, there’s a fabulous new book at the library: The Writer’s Garden, since apparently, there’s a connection between authors and gardening as well. A chapter is devoted to more than twenty authors, such as Roald Dahl, Agatha Christie, Ernest Hemingway, and Virginia Wolfe. We learn about their gardens and grounds, and gain an understanding how it may have influenced their thinking and inspired their writing.  Sometimes there’s a direct link between the author and the book. Jane Austin’s time in brother’s elegant Park Estate surely influenced garden themes in Pride and Prejudice and Mansfield Park. Other garden influences are more oblique. For example, Karen Blixen shares her passion for the beauty of nature in her book Out of Africa, based on her time spent in Kenya. So, it’s not surprising that her gardens in her native Denmark reflected an understanding of the importance of creating natural habitats and biodiversity remarkably advanced for her time. I was thrilled with the chapter on Frances Hodgson Burnett. I can’t be the only one who felt The Secret Garden was written just for her. Burnett spent nearly a decade at Great Matham Hall gardening and writing. She planted more than 300 rose bushes, some which meandered up fruit trees she insisted be reclaimed. We read, “She set up a table and a chair under the trees and wrote every morning-accompanied by a tame robin that would later make an appearance in The Secret Garden”. Be still my swelling heart! Visiting and website information for all the author’s gardens are noted in the appendix which are often located in the UK. (What is it about English gardeners and writers?!) This oversize book includes some stunningly luscious photos. O...more

review: Big trigger alert for this one-stomach clenching to read, but so important not to turn a blind eye to the violence against women around the world. MukBig trigger alert for this one-stomach clenching to read, but so important not to turn a blind eye to the violence against women around the world. Mukwede's courage in addressing atrocities even at risk to his own and family's lives is inspiring. As he points out, these issues affect everyone, including the men who have been indoctrinated and twisted to commit depraved acts without conscience. And though Mukwege explores women's experiences around the world, "This is the story of the Congo, one of the richest counties in the world that has been laid low by 150 years of foreign occupation, dictatorship and ruthless exploitation". The richness comes from the world's richest deposits of copper, uranium, lithium. diamonds and gold. Personally I thought about how my life is enriched by modern technology without much thought to the origin I was encouraged to examine my country's role in ignoring genocide and covertly interfering with foreign governments.I commend Muskwege for managing to find hope and healing on his journey, but it's clear to me we have so much further to travel.The Power of Women is a powerful bookNF...more
